ENTRY            14484   20260331   20260617   20260617       1529
SUBENT        14484001   20260331   20260617   20260617       1529
BIB                 12         37
TITLE      Measurement of the 64Zn,47Ti(n,p) cross sections
           using a DD neutron generator for medical isotope
           studies
AUTHOR     (A.S.Voyles,M.S.Basunia,J.C.Batchelder,J.D.Bauer,
           T.A.Becker,L.A.Bernstein,E.F.Matthews,P.R.Renne,
           D.Rutte,M.A.Unzueta,K.A.Van Bibber)
REFERENCE  (J,NIM/B,410,230,2017)
           #doi:10.1016/j.nimb.2017.08.021
INSTITUTE  (1USAUCX,1USABRK,1USALRL)
           (1USAUSA) Berkeley Geochronology Center, Berkeley,
           CA 94709, USA
FACILITY   (NGEN,1USAUCX) The High-Flux Neutron Generator (HFNG),
           a DD neutron generator at the University of California,
            Berkeley.
INC-SPECT  A 100 keV deuterium beam was extracted at 1.3 mA,
           creating a flux of approximately 1.3*10**7
           neutrons/cm2*s on the target.
DETECTOR   (HPGE) Two detectors were used in this measurement.
           An Ortec 80% High-Purity Germanium (HPGe) detector
           and an Ortec planar Low-Energy Photon Spectrometer
            (LEPS).
METHOD     (ACTIV) After irradiation, the co-loaded targets were
           removed from the HFNG and transferred to a counting
           lab, where their induced activities could be measured
           via gamma ray spectroscopy. The cross sections were
           measured in ratio to the 113In(n,n')113mIn and
           115In(n,n')115mIn inelastic scattering reactions on
           co-irradiated indium samples.
ERR-ANALYS (DATA-ERR) Statistical and systematic uncertainties.
           The uncertainties in photopeak counts are a
           combination of the fit error and counting statistics.
CORRECTION No summing corrections needed to be made since all of
           the gammas are either non-coincident or formed in a
           back-to-back annihilation event.
STATUS     (APRVD) Approved by M.S.Basunia and A.S.Voyles on
           April 9, 2026.
HISTORY    (20260331C) BP
